    {
        "content": "<p>Looking at <code>comap_family</code>, my first thought is to try to factor it into two parts: constructing a measurable space from a family of measurable spaces, and pulling back a measurable space along a function</p>",
        "id": 213813122,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603125792
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the latter we already have, that's <code>comap</code>, and the former is the lattice operation on <code>measurable_space</code> (which is a complete lattice IIRC)</p>",
        "id": 213813218,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603125841
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would the product be the sigma algebra generated by the finite dimensional cylinder sets?</p>",
        "id": 213815192,
        "sender_full_name": "Golol",
        "timestamp": 1603126797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's just <code>\\bigcap i, m i</code></p>",
        "id": 213815298,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603126831
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's the supremum (or infimum, I always get them mixed up) of the family of measurable spaces</p>",
        "id": 213815392,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603126874
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you certainly don't need any <code>generate_from</code> stuff, and that will hugely simplify the proofs</p>",
        "id": 213815524,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603126911
    },
    {
