        "timestamp": 1603127935
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think they are, more or less</p>",
        "id": 213817530,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603127958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh that makes me realize, I actually wanted to do this for a family f_i -&gt; \\b_i, the target spaces should change. I should generalize it.<br>\nMy plan is to follow a script I have on stochastic processes. There is this basic theorem which tells you that the obvious choices for sigma algebras for your stochastic process are the same and you dont have to worry, would be nice to have that.</p>",
        "id": 213817531,
        "sender_full_name": "Golol",
        "timestamp": 1603127958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The point I'm making is that you don't really need this definition because it factors cleanly into two more reusable parts (about which we already have a bunch of theorems)</p>",
        "id": 213817650,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603128005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you wanted the measurable spaces to change, it would just become <code>⨆ i, (m i).comap (f i)</code> instead</p>",
        "id": 213817802,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1603128087
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah yes yes, I realized that. I just want to practice doing some \"theorybuilding\" in lean. And if an earlier definition in the theory is inefficient, then that  can be generalized later I suppose.</p>",
        "id": 213818296,
        "sender_full_name": "Golol",
        "timestamp": 1603128334
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, as always it is getting the definitions right that is the hard part</p>",
